{"cursor":"9667","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{| {{Infobox Ship Image |Ship image= |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox Ship Career\n|Hide header= |Ship country=US |Ship flag= |Ship name= |Ship namesake=Philip\nMichael Joyce |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=Consolidated Steel Corporation,\nOrange, Texas |Ship laid down= 8 March 1943 |Ship launched=26 May 1943 |Ship\nacquired= |Ship commissioned=30 September 1943 |Ship decommissioned=17 June 1960\n|Ship reclassified=DER-317, 13 September 1950 |Ship in service= |Ship out of\nservice= |Ship struck=1 December 1972 |Ship reinstated= |Ship honours= |Ship\nfate=Sold for scrapping 11 September 1973 |Ship status= |Ship notes= }}\n{{Infobox Ship Characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship\ndisplacement=1,253 tons standard 1,590 tons full load |Ship\nlength=306 feet (93.27 m) |Ship beam=36.58 feet (11.15 m)\n|Ship draft=10.42 full load feet (3.18 m) |Ship\npropulsion=4 FM diesel engines, 4 diesel-generators,\n6,000 shp (4.5 MW), 2 screws |Ship speed=21 knots\n(39 km/h) |Ship range=9,100 nmi. at 12 knots (17,000 km\nat 22 km/h) |Ship complement=8 officers, 201 enlisted |Ship sensors= |Ship\nEW= |Ship armament= |Ship armour= |Ship armor= |Ship aircraft= |Ship aircraft\nfacilities= |Ship notes= }}\n|}\n\n'USSJoyce(DE-317)' was an built for the U.S. Navy during World War II. She\nserved in the Atlantic Ocean and the Pacific Ocean and provided destroyer escort\nprotection against submarine and air attack for Navy vessels and convoys.\n\nShe was named in honor of Ensign Philip Michael Joyce who was killed in action\non 19 February 1942 during the bombing of Darwin, Australia. She was laid down 8\nMarch 1943 by the Consolidated Steel Corp., Orange, Texas; launched 26 May 1943;\nsponsored by Mrs. Harold T. Joyce, mother of Ensign Joyce; and commissioned 30\nSeptember 1943, Lt. Comdr. R. Wilcox, USCG, in command.\n","linknr":313,"url":"USS_Joyce_(DE-317)","recorded":1374766357,"links":["/w/index.php?t